At the end of the trading day, the Prague stock market was negative.
After Tuesday morning's fall, the Prague stock market recovered its losses.
The share trading in ČEZ reached almost half of the usual daily trading.
On Tuesday, as the market began, the Prague stock market rebounded from the previous day's fall, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the drop is due to the fall in Wall Street stock.
The market reaction to the result of the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilise the US financial sector, is thus also perceptible here.
Shares fall in Asia
Asian stocks fell dramatically on Tuesday, although the indices managed to erase some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng index of the Hong Kong stock exchange lost four percent during trading, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock market movement on the Hong Kong stock exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to his index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation about the US bailout will affect financial markets around the world", observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, the US legislature should resume negotiations and pass the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could be affected.
The bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, which it was supposed to spend up to $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
The lawmakers rejected President George Bush's call for support for the project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the economy as a whole.
The US stock market was in a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indices experiencing the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having last seen a fall of this magnitude in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it became clear that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gives in: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial aid agreement to the US financial system.
It will be put to a vote early next week.
The U.S. legislature made a decisive turn in the negotiations for a $700 billion bailout of the U.S. financial system.
But success is not guaranteed.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to a vote, Congressmen must finalize a number of details of the agreement.
The financial support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says Barney Frank, chairman of the House banking and financial regulation committee.
According to sources, by Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement of the adoption of the bailout plan should be a major first psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
Given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, a 'disillusionment' will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differences about what the market stabilization package should look like", Democratic Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to finalize the government's foundation.
The Commission is expected to buy back from financial corporations the unsold real estate assets which are causing financial corporations considerable losses and threatening the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be continued, but I think we are on the right track", says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has had a considerable impact on the falling stock markets.
According to Senator Harry Reid, the Democratic Party, lawmakers are working to get Congress to reach a final agreement by Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading starts in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect trading on Monday.
At the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the vote will take place in both Houses of the US Congress, nor whether the negotiations may be blocked at the last moment by some problem.
The legislators hope it will be passed in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount intended for the support of the scheme shall be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion dollars, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not doing its job, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount in two stages: first, an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr Bush welcomed the progress made in the negotiations
While the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of voting against it.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain financing for the purchase of bad real estate, whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush himself is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr. Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Restriction of gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on financial program accountability, taxpayer protection from losses, the deduction agreement, the timing of the plan.
The new law also provides for a limitation of the golden parachutes for directors of participating companies and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also provides for assistance for property owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new mortgage payments for repurchase, while reducing the monthly payments to the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is because we don't know what the mechanism and price of buying back the troubled assets will be.
This will be a decisive point in deciding on the division of losses between the financial sector and the government", Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not, according to Marek, that important.
"It is far more important that the congressmen agree, this week, that they support this plan and that they will enact it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is the most important at the moment", Marek stressed.
A fight that has gone to extremes: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We'll give you advice on how to choose.
While virtually every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons to get a self-reader.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end gramophone for the house to play the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
First, such music products are not released on vinyl, and, from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
If you have a stack of vinyl records of art rock, jazz, or blues, you are probably dreaming of such a record.
The same is true of music on the go, which is compressed music, to put it simply - MP3 music.
There are categories according to price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty in buying headphones for twenty crowns at the market.
There are two extremes, and there's enough room for everyone in between.
There's a lot to choose from.
Battery life is also crucial
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions that are, of course, unknown to most mobile phones.
No other device today is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the basic functions of making phone calls and sending SMS, it is capable of reading music and films, recording them, has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a little computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge can roast meat and no television can take pictures, we are witnessing a miracle.
The universal nature of the mobile phone is not without its drawbacks.
The more functions you use, the shorter the interval between two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy drains.
Few mobile phones are capable of playing music for ten to twelve hours, but in most cases this figure is much lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the more rudimentary ones) are much better.
If you have a cheap phone, you can expect it to play music for only a few hours.
If you do call occasionally, make sure you have a second charger for work - even for more expensive devices.
This will not be a problem for MP3 players, which are capable of continuous operation for at least 9 hours after recharging, including those with lower performance.
Another problem arises when recording music on the mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly onto the memory card, but few card readers know how to do so without a discount, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As for the players, you don't need any software, except for the iPod.
All you have to do is fill the music device from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobile phones and players will create a media library themselves, sorted by the artist's name, the album title, the style, or the user's judgment.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobile has more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, pay particular attention to the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If music is for you, essentially, background noise and if you are going to listen to it for a limited time during the day, for example while taking the tram, you can use any mobile phone that plays MP3s.
Almost every mobile phone today is capable of this.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to what music formats your phone or player is capable of playing.
They can all read MP3s, and the vast majority of the music that's going to come to you will be in that format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also play WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
All you have to do is visit the corresponding operator's (or another provider's) web pages from your mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason for obtaining a musical motive.
Unfortunately, the supply of operators is poor and is limited, in most cases, to rapidly manufactured radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive with them.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just take your phone out of your pocket, and you forgot your MP3 player at home.
It is also important if you always have headphones or a hands-free with a connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which are available on almost all mobile phones, but with a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical motifs is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can get a walkman that's already very decent.
However, in most cases you will be limited by the lack of an outlet for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped ones, which also have an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
The readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Anyone can order the most basic readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our selection).
The control is a minimum of functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette player, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly plugged mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
What to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can even get away with 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and you still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or a Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose rather specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent MP3 control keys, and thus the ease of control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
The first virtual operator will enter the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
But we are still lacking something - a virtual operator, which would force the traditional operators to lower prices.
He may not be gone for long.
We have already mentioned many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) confirmed that the price of an SMS was higher in the Czech Republic than in the rest of the EU.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the area of roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation: SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of the Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no room in the Czech Republic for another operator, is in chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently out of luck (and, moreover, it would now have difficulty finding frequencies).
There is another possibility - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable price drop, to which the traditional operators also had to react.
Yet even before the advent of such disruptors as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it became apparent that there was still room for such operators and that they could be really successful.
We do not have to look too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the Mobilking virtual operator.
In just six months, the operator managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
The Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators are positioning themselves as low-cost operators - offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers text messages at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertising move.
This operator is specifically targeted at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - a carrier they like and can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual carrier.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work here too.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a segment approach, which is the basis for most virtual operators.
This is especially true since it is relatively saturated in terms of service supply".
Czech mobile operators say no chance
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promising.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our area", said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were in any event not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
GTS Novera, which would like to take a further step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not been hiding its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator for quite some time.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to make progress in the negotiations", says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be bright.
From unofficial reports, it seems that we may be able to welcome the first virtual operator as early as the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
At the moment, no one with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us", said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project that could serve as a basis".
She adds: 'It is virtually impossible for a virtual carrier to appear on T-Mobile's network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a short time, we should have a concrete agreement now.'
Vodafone is instead focusing on fulfilling requests for its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in this regard: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think is the most important input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet".
Responsible authorities: in sync with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
What good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators are as good as thieves at a fair, as the rioting that accompanied the creation of U:fon.
The biggest pressure on ČTÚ, when U:fon was created, was the pressure exerted by T-Mobile.
This is shown by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
Today, however, U:fon is used as an argument against accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: 'Competition in the mobile market has also recently been intensified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile RT market, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would place high demands on the market, and especially on its services.'
But given the attitude of mobile operators as follows, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems to be disconcerting.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS) is the sole owner of the Office.
The Commission has adopted its typical position on this issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned concerning the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer of potential interested parties has not shown sufficient interest for conventional operators", explained Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS External Relations Department in response to our question.
A statement thus formulated would not be surprising from operators' representatives.
But such a statement from an agency which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than confusing.
The Commission has also been asked to examine the possibility of a new approach to the problem of the use of mobile telephony in the Community.
However, it is apparent that the ÚOHS has no interest in pressing for fair market operation and lower prices.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which emerges from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence naturally arises.
Similarly, a price of petrol which is strictly identical at all petrol stations is probably due to chance and to the fierce competition.
'The Office has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has a correspondingly increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The telecommunications regulator probably lacks the tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators", Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at all times.
And the mobile operator has a pretty logical monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
Even without accepting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are behaving in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is a common communication trick, by which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not include an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one's watching, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo-operators, several of which operate in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partly public.
In most cases, this refers to firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The trick is that the company makes the operator look like a conventional business customer, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you mention happens, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would look into and could result in a termination of the collaboration with the company in question", Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is unlikely that such activity would not have reached the heads of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, this may involve thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The activities of these firms bring them substantial profits and, at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, as ordinary mobile phone customers do".
This is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
Furthermore, there is another question at ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual terms prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable drop in the price of services.
In almost all countries where virtual operators were established, the traditional operators were making more or less efforts to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - too small or even too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries have intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they finally achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory agencies are treating this issue like a hot potato that is thrown away by passing it on to a nearby target.
In the light of our experience, we cannot shake the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the hammer.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator appears soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four songs of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech National Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my country?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with male or female solo singing, a choral performance and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The arrangements for the anthem were written by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers and the choir had a good diction, so that the words were understood, that they sang simultaneously", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first heard in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of the Savetiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, with music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
