The Czech Republic's public transport authorities will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday.
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, it is accessible to about 100,000 people who have Opencard smart cards.
Passengers can buy a 30-day or 90-day coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, coupons can also be purchased online on the Dopravní podnik website: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people enjoyed the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store can forget forever about the ticket counters at the metro stations, where they have hitherto had to wait in long queues to get paper tickets.
They will buy their voucher online and it will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these points, passengers have access to a ticket office with trained staff who will help them with online purchases and also record the voucher they have purchased on their card", says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the lobby of several metro stations.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, the ticket composting machines remind us, and passengers may have already noticed them at the subway stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
A vending machine will check the coupon instead of the driver.
The automata that will be running tomorrow are easy to use.
Just enter the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
The main routes to the capital are the suburban trains and the bus lines 300 to 499, which are used mainly by the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia.
"In the integrated trains at Pražská integrovaná doprava (integrated transport in Prague), the controllers are equipped with card readers, with which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of the coupons", explained ticket controller Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation, which designs Prague's public transport schedules.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver's trunk.
When boarding, it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the indicated place on the side of the cash register.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing simpler than asking the driver for this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take the commuter buses and do not remember the expiry date of their voucher can re-join the ATMs, which were originally used to record vouchers on the card.
This is where the information about the validity of their document will be displayed on the device's screen.
