The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This is according to a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (South Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the U.S. president with such a desire.
This is one of the results of a letter kept in a private archive, which is now in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
The Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter pleaded with the American president not to allow "šumavská župa" (a forest region in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have a good understanding of the situation and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops are coming to German territory are not oppressors and enemies, but liberators", reads the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of the Šumava".
Since the supposed promise of allying with Czechoslovakia - knowing the Czech national character - is nothing but brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take the Šumava protectorate into his own hands for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state which oppresses and destroys minorities and which did nothing to help the Allied victory without considering the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants", the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would have to organise, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US, or live under US patronage.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans must have at least foreseen the possibility of being expelled from the republic, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would give the Sudetenlanders some sort of autonomy.
Others thought that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to learn Czech.
"They thought that when they returned home, the Czech language would be of benefit to them", says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that the Beneš Decrees would lead to their being expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety measure in Czech history.
A way of characterizing the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of Minister Aleš Řebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign, which cost 150 million euros, will be shown on television, radio, in films, on the Internet and in leaflets.
It should discourage speeding and drinking.
But also remind them to fasten their seat belts before starting.
The aim is to reach the consciousness of young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians and even professional drivers.
What's going to be in the commercials?
Especially personal stories that will attack the emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a pool of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay".
Which must symbolize that one can pay for one moment of inattention with one's life.
The ads will haunt the audience until 2010.
The Ministry has taken inspiration from similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where it is common to see images with dramatic images of accident victims.
He believes that this will lead to a reduction in the number of accidents and fatalities on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The sugar and whip strategy against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whipping system.
For example, sugar is represented by saving time by roasting on a red fire.
Whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers", says Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at the Na Homolce Hospital.
This is why we need press campaigns and, above all, negative advertising, says the psychologist.
He said that the signs warning drivers of danger are already less effective.
"When a static warning sign is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will not notice it", said Kořán.
Olmert would give up almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace.
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli provisional government, spoke in favour of the return of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published by the Yedioth Ahronoth newspaper on Monday.
"We have to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all the (occupied) territories, if not all", Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), since without that, peace will not be made", he added.
He admits that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants security in Jerusalem, and especially does not want to be crushed by tractors and bulldozers, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem", Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July that killed several people and injured dozens.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historic places" located inside the Old City.
"Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It will not work", he later stressed.
Withdrawal from the Golan Heights
Olmert also spoke in favour of Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he considered an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace agreement with Syria.
But this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria on the basis of a withdrawal from the Golan", he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with Hezbollah (the Shiite movement); they will have to give up their constant support for the terrorism of Hamas (the Shiite movement), Al-Qaeda (the terrorist network), as well as the jihad (holy war) in Iraq", the Prime Minister said.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards on the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is prohibited
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency coach near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether the stewards and passengers can move around inside the coach during the journey.
"If the law is strictly and formally observed, the activity of a steward is contrary to the traffic law", says transportation ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck crossing the bus' path.
The girl was sadly sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
The bus may have an accident or even brake abruptly, even while the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance buses of the Student Agency do not have standing places; this was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company's director Radim Jančura.
"We have discussed this with the ministry and at first they prohibited all travel by passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the journey provided they have their own seat", he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no single legal interpretation of the steward's role - no legal prescription deals with this role.
Moreover, no legal requirement prevents the carrier from offering services.
The road transport law only knows the term 'vehicle receiver'; it does not define his rights and duties,' adds Hanzelka, spokesman for the company.
Josef Pokorný, director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law deals sufficiently with the problem.
"It all depends on whether the bus has a permit to offer standing seats.
It's all in that", he says.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing places and a higher permitted speed and long distance buses without standing place with the highest permitted maximum speed and seats fitted with seat belts.
Like on a plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert in road safety at BESIP, does not see the shifting of stewards on board as a major problem.
"There is no danger in regular traffic, which can be compared to the situation in air traffic control.
There, too, it is not certain when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant may hit her head".
"If the bus had brake suddenly, the laws of physics would obviously apply.
Just like a city bus or a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards by internal regulations", he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not solved.
Jančura is ready to cancel these services
Student Agency is the only bus operator to offer steward services.
He hires two hundred.
Even after the accident, the manager doesn't consider their job a risky one.
"However, as soon as I feel that it is a risky business, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on board.
It would also reduce costs", he says.
The reason given by the director of Asiana Alexei Litvine for the absence of stewards in his vehicles is safety, which, in comparison with SA, provides a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses, we've been opposed to it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident", he told Týden.cz a year ago.
A great tragedy has occurred.
A young hostess from the Plzeň area, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop lane without using a blinker and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he approached him by his right side.
Jančura refuses to accept that the two seats reserved for the stewards' rest have been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these places, they are blocked".
The company plans to sue the truck driver.
As far as the girl's family is concerned, the agency will not wait for the court's decision, but as far as financial compensation is concerned, it is also counting on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight.
An amendment to the law, which has been in the works for over a year by a group of 30 experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarification as to the movements of stewards on board the bus.
"But it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, it is not so much interested in buses as in the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of the mobile phone while driving", says expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers", spokesman Hanzelka concluded, adding that the control of bus safety is under the authority of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The Düsseldorfer hopes were once rested on Frankfurt.
The letter from the WestLB management committee to the employees of the company was full of words.
The merger of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institute with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank could create the "central financial market institution of the Sparkasse financial group", according to the letter published on Monday.
WestLB would provide a 'block of jurisdiction' with a doubled sustainable productivity in such a case.
