Sleepless nights for the shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
It is fortunate that the politician used the word 'relatively' and that he hinted that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis movements.
This one did happen this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed on the DAX, obtained a loan of 1 billion from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are being issued for up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, the subsidiary Depfa is the one that bears the losses.
The State financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself very short term for long term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of distrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had been reduced by 95 per cent to EUR 2,37 million, and the equity ratio had also fallen slightly from 1,6 to 1,45 per cent.
Current and net financial transactions were down to zero compared with the same period last year, while earnings from the allocation of fixed assets and liabilities and the cancellation of provisions in credit operations were down by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
Only the substantial profits from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest on the tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern's companies, have been able to moderate the profit shortfall of around 16%.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had firstly speculated badly on industrial real estate loans, which were subsequently affiliated to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more involved in infrastructure projects and in financing joint projects between private and public investors (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must make depreciation payments which should have a material and significant effect on the calculation of the group's profits and losses, but which is still rather vague.
The fact is, the dividends have been cut.
By 2007, they had been cut to two thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major investor in State and infrastructure since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is more robust than other institutions dependent on refinancing on the interbank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has again become considerably cheaper as banks have accumulated liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing facility for a part of the Depfa loan portfolio - about EUR 50 billion - each year.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing needs are covered by medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of the international financial markets which are largely out of order at present.
Other sources say that the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE's Chairman Georg Funke, however, explained that Hypo Real Estate should no longer have to resort to medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (Bafin) assume that the market capacity of the Hypo Real group is now secured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope.
However, given the dynamics and the immensity of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not inconceivable that the whole of the funding should not be used.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest reports, still on the verge of insolvency on Sunday evening, this at least temporary bailout will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell by 75 per cent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While the main debts have barely moved, the secondary lending prices are falling.
The most affected are investment funds of the former Württemberg Hypo subsidiary and those with a life beyond 2009.
The Hypo Real Estate bonds previously appeared to be an alternative speculative investment, but their value must now be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international banking system following the net worsening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself which brought the crisis into the establishment through the buy-out of Depfa.
As long as the less affected issuing institutions, governments and commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that the lags will be resolved over time.
Or what no one dares to hope for now will happen - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of renewed rumors of partial nationalisation, the probability that security was approaching has now become a mere hope.
This should give sleepless nights primarily to long-term creditors on the decision whether to separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can always use what they have drawn a line on to postpone losses for the next few years on the next automatically levied capital gains tax.
Sylvana and the secrets of the box in Bento
When Sylvana Hiltrop, 16, has to go to Tachibana High School for the first day, the girls start to laugh: German is so "kawaii"!
