Rats have feelings too
A rat or a cockroach fleeing danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness which I or anyone else has not been able to prove up to now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into difficultly practicable terrain because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what many other animals do: it fakes death, flies or attacks.
Humans behave in the same way, which is why some scientists infer a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience into that of animals.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other creatures.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including our awareness of who we are, and our ability to predict and make decisions, it's reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another significant feature may lie in the linguistic nature of Man: since a large part of his existence is linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In that case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would certainly be influenced by it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This makes it difficult to determine what the conscience might be like in other animals.
If this is internal and subjective and cannot be measured or, because of this particular hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
We could look at the consciousness processes of animals without considering their content, and that's exactly what happened in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, we focus more on the neural correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does that do for emotions?
I'm concluding that an emotional system like fear is activated in a conscious brain of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its aftermath, such as body reactions) takes over the vivid memory.
So, emotion is closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates, and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our fickle nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to imput them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities originate in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brain stem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could well have participated in cross-sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as such in both cases: how could we verify that rats and humans feel the same when they behave in similar ways?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels fear?
I don't think that similar behaviour is enough to prove that we've all had the same experiences.
Of course, the nerve comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stem, whereas cockroaches don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the source of the sensations?
And even if we could prove it in humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is considerable progress on the nervous level, since the same measurements are made in rats and humans.
