In a Separate City, Pride and the Trials of Black Life
Hidden in its vast parkland development, a few miles from sunny, bright and gigantic Orlando, lies a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first all-black city to be incorporated, the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, that description she made in 1935, is not so easy to make today". The city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of guavas, two schools and no prison.
It's now a pilgrimage town
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora Festival held annually in Eatonville, to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in many ways, the city she describes -- which became a tourist destination thanks to its inclusion in the Florida Tourist Guide published by The Depression-era Federal Writers' Project -- remains a place of its own.
It is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston told how the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knows so little of us, doesn't know what he is missing".
Even though this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has also called for an open dialogue on the issue of race, many here remain wary of the outside world's gaze.
"We are very careful about how we tell the story", said Hortense Jones, 59, a longtime resident and the town's oldest parishioner.
"it must be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and fighting.
It represents both a historic model of a black takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of rural Southern black culture - sometimes disregarded, sometimes acclaimed - that recalls the birth of American slavery.
Which would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, dialect-filled books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed this town, located just off of Route 17, into a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida, ending in a chapter of black history and human drama.
As bold as a big box in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
"On the left of the road", she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its well-preserved gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always took care of, though he could hardly read or write.
She further mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything else that passersby can use.
So in barely a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone liked.
Zora described the reality well: "Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the young girls of Johnson whom Hurston immortalized, quoted the colourless songs, performed by men who praised their beauty".
She added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town without warning, riding in a large Chevrolet with a cigarette in his mouth and wearing trousers here, where even today people are proud of their traditional clothes.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed at her.
"People were always happy to see Zora", he said.
But he added, rocking in his backyard chair overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was likely baptized, that "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville and the world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a private grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she lived.
In Eatonville, no big memorial, no plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered to the world", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A turning point came in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane highway through the city, replacing Kennedy Boulevard, the community's two-lane main street.
Orlando's development has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made as Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, ended the community's relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the race controversy led to hatred at the community's doors.
"At that time, a bunch of young white men would come and throw oranges or other objects at people sitting on the side", Mr. Franklin said.
"one lady has even died".
They threw a watermelon out of their car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, calling its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorifying my race".
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some respects, has diluted Eatonville's cohesion and weakened youth confidence.
"Black children used to be kissed - I remember well - we kissed our master in the morning, and in the evening", said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the Eatonville Community Conservation, a nonprofit group.
This continued, she added, until the time when teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white - I mean there's a cultural line here", said Ms. Nathiri.
Civil rights, by the way, allowed for the creation of space for many other Zora Neale Hurston-black writers, actors and artists who went beyond prejudice, such as herself, armed with a cheerful self-confidence and such lines of conduct as: "how can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
I can't do this".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston's anonymous grave and began a struggle to revive his reputation.
Five years later, a critically acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a true bestseller, reintroduced her to the American canon.
The highway project came just as Eatonville's most famous girl had regained her charm.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community started to organize a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of the highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the opening of the festival two years later, and many return in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the county rejected the proposed highway.
"The five-lane highway fiasco, extremely fast, a real civic pride", said Ms. Nathiri.
Miss Boyd summed it up by saying, "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been a historic city since 1998.
A new one-theme library (of course named Hurston) opened in 2006 on beautifully landscaped Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back alley on a rainy summer day, as small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(now 90 percent black)
Foreigners who come to learn about Eatonville's history, its purpose, are still treated with caution.
Permission is required for most interviews, and some things - like the walls of the old Eatonville church, painted by the white man, depicting black men in the fields - should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Miss Jones, a courageous teacher with a soft spot for bright red, are still afraid that their island community will be understood.
However, as Hurston Festival expanded, a certain level of local pride emerged.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw his entire race: beautiful, problematic and all, no better or worse, but as proud, creative, bulky, crazy and mixed up as other ethnic and racial groups in America.
It is genuine civic affection that is heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police force, which needs additional reinforcements.
And even for the younger ones, like 11-year-old Alondra and Alexia Kenon, the Winter Park twins, they seem to have learned the description of Eatonville correctly.
