"I photograph the master off stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels or foreign clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, free from all tension to achieve the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The other is the person.
Inseparable except in the intimacy, in those moments unknown to the general public, where one discovers through intimate gestures and stealthy looks the artists who don't bother to come on stage.
German Günther Bauer combines the theatricality of a few stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of the artists in "Flamenco - people".
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the Flemish Photography Month program, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, growing every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists who are able to convey on stage passion, sadness, joy... by capturing the audience.
To capture moments of the personalities of these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the moments of the personality of flamenco stars".
With the "People's Song of the Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits which, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recall the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the dance or the singing itself, but the personality and character of the artist that captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic has been the constant of this work which is being presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are among the selection made from around seventy photographed artists.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people's portraits, get to know them and be able to enter their lives for a moment or so.
I think in photography, portrait is the most difficult kind.
You're in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or who only give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at 20 Rue de la Mata (a street parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule), which will be open until October 16.
