Repeat drinkers will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants drivers who have had more than three administrative penalties for alcohol, to have a system installed in their vehicle that prevents the vehicle from starting when drunk, or if it is not breathing.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now reflected in the Minister of State's report, which considers it a pilot project for a year.
The aim is to reintegrate the driver by offering them road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Foundation Institute of Technology for Motor Safety will also participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers arrested for more than one drunk driving offense are in the car.
The alcohol lock would avoid this as it is a system plugged into the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow first; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than the permitted level.
The cost is more than EUR 1,000 and is borne by the driver.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced infringements by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 lives each year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, reform by penal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet commercially available on the Spanish market, although some industrial and commercial vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
The European Parliament will vote on an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party to install the system in school buses, as has been done in France.
