Talking while sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very awake and tell us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens, it may surprise you, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a mild sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It's pretty common, especially in children and teenagers.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month, etc.), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often associated with other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it occurs also varies greatly.
He may speak in a low, quiet voice, with isolated words, whispering or conversing with shouts, tears, long speeches...
If sleepwalking becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to see if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for the problem.
We said it's a mild alteration, so there's no treatment unless it's related to another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it's related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
As soon as the sleepwalking occurs, try to remain calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and the next day he will not remember what happened.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's no use, since he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even though he talks, he's sleeping and resting.
Remember, if he is very anxious repeatedly, it is wise to consult a doctor or to find out what is causing the child so much anxiety.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not usual), do not be tempted to ask him questions for information.
You're not getting anything, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Also, you will hear what he is saying, but you will not know what he is dreaming, so be careful how you interpret the information and draw your own conclusions.
Never tell a child that you can ask him questions at night to find out his secrets.
Not even in a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's not a bad thing, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
