Sarkozy meets angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
In view of the demonstration of force by the fishermen who on Monday severely disrupted the access to several Breton and Norman ports, the President of the Republic decided to go to the port of Guilvinec, in Finistère, on Tuesday morning to meet their representatives.
The latter promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hoped that he would "come with concrete proposals".
The presidential visit coincides with a general meeting of the 'crisis committee' set up by Breton fishermen to seek measures to tackle the skyrocketing price of diesel, which has reached a record high of more than 1.14 euros per litre on average.
According to Elysee spokesman David Martinon, the President "will discuss with them solutions that can be devised to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the employment and remuneration conditions of seafarers".
Nicolas Sarkozy is firmly expected by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they conducted snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing traffic jams of nearly 10 km.
The Quiberon marina was also blocked, but the routes to Belle Isle were not stopped.
A filter dam has been installed on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors showed their determination on Monday by burning tires and pallets at dawn in front of the fuel depots at the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau and Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic and Channel fronts, such as Sands d'Olonne in the Vendée, where the trawlers remained at berth, or Le Havre, where some 20 ships blocked the movement of merchant ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantique region, stopped the blockade of the important Total refinery in Donges in the evening.
The Boulogne-sur-Mer authorities have decided to wait for the meeting on Wednesday at the ministry to decide on possible action.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" is due to decide on Tuesday what action to take on the movement and whether it will participate in the meeting scheduled at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the National Fisheries Committee, which did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not give up anything" and "they do not want to move to Paris", said Liliane Cariou, president of the Lorient fisheries committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per litre but estimate that the threshold of profitability of a boat is reached only with less than EUR 0.30 per litre of diesel.
