The Brazilian aircraft manufacturer is on the brink of 215 aircraft delivered this year despite the threat of recession looming over the global economy.
The world's fourth largest aircraft manufacturer, Embraer, is maintaining its 2008 delivery forecast with 215 aircraft delivered, its chairman, Fredrico Fleury Curado, has confirmed.
In the first six months, the aircraft manufacturer delivered 97 aircraft.
The Brazilian manufacturer has high hopes for the Chinese market, particularly for its aircraft in the range of 30 to 120 seats.
To date, Embraer has delivered 41 aircraft to Chinese customers in eight years.
AIG is considering divesting more than 15% of its assets
The American International Group, which has been bailed out by the U.S. monetary authorities, is planning to sell more than 15 percent of its assets to pay back the $85 billion in advance, according to the Sunday edition of the Financial Times.
AIG is prepared to consider selling most of its business beyond its international life insurance and retirement business in the United States, the newspaper said, citing sources familiar with the matter.
The board of directors of AIG met on Sunday evening to discuss possible divestments, according to the FT.
No confirmation could be obtained from AIG.
The assets AIG is considering divesting include its air leasing subsidiary International Lease Financial Corp., its 59% stake in reinsurer Transatlantic Holdings, and its real estate portfolio and private equity investments, the FT adds.
No final decision has been taken on these divestments, FT continues.
AIG must quickly raise liquidity to repay the $85 billion loan from the Federal Reserve, at the risk of the US authorities taking 80% of its capital, diluting the existing shareholders proportionately.
