The New York Stock Exchange reported a historic drop on Monday after the House of Representatives rejected the Paulson plan to bail out the banks: the Dow Jones dropped 6.98%, a loss never seen before, approaching 800 points, and the Nasdaq 9.14%.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) fell by 777.68 points to 100.365.45 points.
In terms of points, the biggest drop in its history (684.81 points) had previously been recorded on 17 September 2001, the day of the resumption of trade after the terrorist attacks of 11 September.
The technology-dominated Nasdaq index fell 199.61 points to 1,983.73 and the enlarged Standard & Poor's 500 index fell 8.81% (or 106.85 points) to 1,106.55 points, according to the final closing figures.
Already depressed at the start of the session, Wall Street sank after the House of Representatives unexpectedly rejected the bank bailout plan that was supposed to restore some stability to the markets.
By 228 votes to 205, the representatives denied Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson the funds he requested.
Almost two out of three Republicans rejected his plan.
"It's a bad signal to the market, which sees Congress unable to pass a plan", said Lindsey Piegza of FTN Financial.
"This shows how much the market was counting on this", she added, fearing that a draft adopted in several days would be "too late".
"If the project is indeed moribund . . . then the relay will quickly be passed to the Fed and other central banks to manage the crisis, which would further tighten credit conditions", warned Brian Bethune, chief economist at Global Insight.
And further accentuating the sense of urgency, "every day brings the downfall of a financial institution" in the United States, Ms Piegza stressed.
After Washington Mutual went bankrupt on Friday, authorities arranged for the purchase of Wachovia's banking business by rival Citigroup.
In Europe, the crisis has accelerated sharply, prompting emergency intervention for banks in the United Kingdom, Benelux, Iceland and Germany, signalling that markets are facing "not just a US crisis, but a global crisis", FTN Financial analyst added.
The bond market has gone up.
The yield on the 10-year Treasury bond fell to 3,632%, from 3,827% on Friday night, and the 30-year yield to 4,161%, from 4,357% the day before.
Obama, winner by points in the first televised duel
The first debate on Friday between the two candidates for the White House was followed by another to see who won, John McCain or Barack Obama.
Not surprisingly, the Republican and Democratic campaign leaders declared their own victory in this televised duel that would have been watched by a third of American families.
Political analyst David Gergen believes that John McCain's performance, while honorable, was not "brilliant" enough to stop his decline in the polls five weeks before the presidential election.
The Gallup Institute, whose opinion poll released on Saturday gives Obama a five-point lead (49 percent to McCain's 44 percent), believes that the Democrats have pulled the trigger.
Among undecided voters, who are the ones that matter, Obama won by 39 percent of the poll, while 25 percent of them gave McCain the win, according to a CBS poll.
Obama should be able to confirm his lead on Thursday with the expected good performance of his running mate, Joseph Biden, in the first and only public debate with his rival, Sarah Palin.
"It would be a mistake to underestimate her.
She has good instincts", warned Bill Clinton this weekend.
The 70-year-old McCain has consistently emphasised his unquestionable experience in foreign policy, while also pointing out the "naivety" of his opponent on these issues which were at the heart of this first face-to-face meeting.
"Senator Obama doesn't seem to understand that"... he repeatedly accused.
"I don't think Senator Obama has the experience and the knowledge to be president", he added.
A point of attack hammered since yesterday in Republican TV commercials.
Obama, on the other hand, emphasized that he represented the future.
He was not discouraged, but he was concise and precise.
He has shown his ability to make the right decisions, and to restore America's image in the world.
"McCain still doesn't understand, while Obama does", a Democratic spot this weekend said, blaming the Republican for not taking full account of the impact of the crisis on "the American on the street".
"During the 90 minutes of debate, John McCain had a lot to say about me, but nothing about you", Obama said yesterday, before 20,000 people gathered for an election rally in North Carolina in the pouring rain.
He didn't even say the words "middle class" or "workers". The financial debacle clearly benefits Obama, who is seen by Americans as the most capable of saving the economy on the brink.
"The coming week could be a turning point", said the influential Democrat Senator Charles Schumer yesterday.
Democratic Representative Rahm Emanuel, a former Clinton administration official, compared Obama's "good economic instincts" to those of Bill Clinton during the 1998 financial crisis.
For the Democratic candidate, the current debacle "is the final verdict of eight years of bad economic policy implemented by George Bush and supported by Senator McCain".
Reaffirming that he would still be able to cut Americans' taxes by 95 percent despite the Wall Street uprisings, the Illinois senator also indicated that achieving the country's eventual energy independence through the promotion of renewable energy was his first priority, with the establishment of a health insurance system.
McCain, on the other hand, wanted to build a fleet of 45 nuclear power plants by 2030.
Both candidates have been cautious in avoiding questions about the $700 billion financial rescue plan passed by Congress last night and extremely unpopular.
In Minsk, "Did you notice that there was an election, you?"
Young people and opponents demonstrated on Sunday evening in the main square of the Belarusian capital to reject the early results of the legislative elections.
Several hundred Belarusians gathered on Sunday evening as soon as the polling stations closed in the central square of Minsk to protest the fraudulent nature of the legislative elections.
While no results had been announced, many young people had come to protest against the power of President Alexander Lukashenko: "The dictator, resign".
Some people admit that they did not even vote. "It's no use, since they will do whatever they want with my vote", says one youth.
They do not believe that the regime which has been appealing to foreign observers in an attempt to get back in touch with the European Union is ready to make a democratic turn.
Sanctions, including visa bans on 40 Belarusian leaders and asset freezes, could be lifted if the election is deemed clean by observers.
They have not been according to the opposition.
"We were kept out of the electoral commissions and our observers could not participate in the counting", lamented Yuri Potemkin, the spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, a heterogeneous grouping of twelve parties.
"It's a cosmetic change", says Alexandre Milinkievitch, a former opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential election and a leader of the pro-European movement, "because it's who counts the votes that counts, and in our country it's the executive.
If the opposition enters parliament, it means they have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry into parliament may mean television space, regional meetings and legislative proposals".
The opposition must therefore enter the political game because 'dialogue with the European Union must begin.
Because if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, goes into crisis, and we don't reform, we risk becoming a Russian protectorate.
We want to be independent".
The opposition fears that the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which monitored the electoral process, will recognise the validity of the vote.
It stresses that the turnout figures appear to be too high, and that the widespread use of early voting (26% of voters in Minsk) has opened the door to all forms of manipulation.
"Did you notice that there was an election?" asked Social Democratic leader Alexandre Kozouline, one of the last two political prisoners released in August this year.
There was no one in the polling stations.
And there will be no more than five opposition MPs in parliament, those who are best suited to power".
The silence of the night falls on October Square.
On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Electoral Commission are congratulating themselves on their success.
Interview - From Blood to Safety
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the blood-tainted scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As is well known, the national blood supply, administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service, was contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In response to this tragedy and public outcry, the Government of Canada in February 1994 instituted a public inquiry, headed by Justice Horace Krever, to find out what had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Krever was delaying in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee with the goal of planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Corporation to supply all other provinces and territories.
"When Héma-Québec started in 1998, only 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we have regained the public's trust", she says, proudly stating that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Decary notes that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, Europe was witnessing the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has been the dominant one since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We have therefore taken one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, namely that when we do not know and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures should be introduced.
In April 1999, therefore, blood was refused to persons who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago it was clearly demonstrated that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This incident showed us that the precautionary principle was sound".
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs), which detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of donors rather than antibodies to the virus, on which previous tests were based.
The researchers say that the NSAIDs have shortened the silent period, which extends from the time when a person is infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected unknowingly and untraceable.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it would take 12 million blood products to get someone infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that people can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing blood transfusions to regain their health", says the head of the Héma-Québec administration.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen's gonna pop up in the system.
Not later than last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion. Like the West Nile virus, it is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a replenishment of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which comprises on average only 3 per cent of eligible Quebecers".
However, any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate their blood are rejected because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is rampant, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but it is even harder to keep them from doing so and to encourage them to become regular blood donors.
"In today's hectic life, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also runs the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
Once considered biomedical waste, the umbilical cord is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and we plan to collect over a thousand per year.
We should start offering them for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", as Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
