Charest set to the north
The Prime Minister does not rule out calling elections before the end of the year
As soon as the Liberal Party's general council was over, Jean Charest visited Jean-Talon, Quebec, yesterday, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected in today's by-election.
'Pushing the limits of our last great northern frontier': this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in the main lines, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his talk, was a projection of a kind of picture mill.
On three huge screens, spectacular pictures of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec as seen through "Google Maps", maps, and so on, were looped.
Big means like election time.
In a press release, the Prime Minister refused to rule out the possibility of holding elections this autumn, although he noted that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic area", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in recent speeches by the Prime Minister, the opening of the North - the territory north of the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, merely explained why the North was "a gem with immense potential", but did not give a timetable, investment amounts or precise priority in future projects.
At most a few avenues of what could be further developed: hydropower, forestry, but especially the mining sector, which is being boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds", according to Charest's list.
This "territory twice the size of France" is our home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it in our country, it is in us", he insisted, as if to show that he was asking for a national founding myth.
He said that Quebec had built up a great deal of links with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future", he added, after taking a dramatic pause to contemplate the huge map behind him.
The north, 70 per cent of Quebec's territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the premier said at the press conference.
"This is a traditional position that has been reiterated by all governments.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and when the opportunity arises I reiterate this position on behalf of the government", he said.
"With climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North", he said, referring to the North-West Passage, which will be open all year round because of melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister feels that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the First Nations and Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially the young.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (formerly a Pequist MP from Ungava), have already started consultations with some 30 communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important role, has started work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a time when "we will give each other a common vision".
The development of the North would be carried out in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be "consistent, orderly and environmentally friendly", he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as continuing with that of previous Liberal Prime Ministers.
"Like the Liberals who came before us, we have thought differently about turning challenges into new opportunities for growth and development".
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a big cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's arrival at the party's headquarters.
One of the resolutions adopted proposed renaming the Beauharnois Power Station into the Adélard-Godbout Dam.
"From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who made the Quiet Revolution and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, who made James Bay, our party has forged the future", said Jean Charest.
He also referred to another conservative reference, the "Roads to the North" programme of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
Speaking about the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr Charest pointed out that it was scheduled to be commissioned in 2012.
"It's between us, but I plan to be there", he told his supporters, who applauded.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of calling a vote this autumn, which the law allows him to do.
He stressed that his schedule was full, however, including a Federation Council mission to China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The General Council of the weekend provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, including "constitutional aspirations" that were passed as a letter to the post: the PLQ demands in particular recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
It also wants Quebec to appoint members of the Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and for the latter to have veto power over decisions taken in Quebec.
The opposition welcomed the outline of the Northern Plan with skepticism.
The Pequiste leader, Pauline Marois, highlighted the Northern Quebec Development Policy that the Landry government had launched in 2001.
She said that the Liberal government, when it came to power in 2003, had abandoned its policy.
If he had done so, "we would be more advanced today", said Ms Marois, alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (a poll taking place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ said they support the government adopting a Northern Plan.
"But what we want is for it not to be just a show", said leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who returned from holiday today.
Letters - A Land Disgraced
It was Mr Vic Toews, former Minister of Justice in the Harper cabinet, who last summer dared to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "shame" for Canada.
The shameful treatment of this woman who has fought tirelessly for justice and who deserves our admiration says as much about the Prime Minister's entourage as it does about Stephen Harper himself.
We are faced with a government which is the only one of all the Western countries involved that has not repatriated its citizen from the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government which does not take into account the fact that Omar Khadr was a very young teenager at the time of the alleged crimes.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, is breaking its word and letting a child soldier die in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a travesty of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
It should be recalled that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, among others, are advocating for Omar Khadr's repatriation so that he can have a fair trial in Canada.
It is the same government that turns a blind eye to torture, not caring that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, perhaps forever after so many years of abuse.
We do not yet realize it, but we are witnessing an insidious erosion of our rights, our freedom and our 'democracy', the word Harper keeps using and which sounds so hollow in his mouth.
The time has come when there is no more morality: one can abuse, torture, imprison arbitrarily a Canadian citizen according to the goodwill of a government leader who has hitherto been a minority (what will happen after October 14...).
Many voters believe that they will find salvation in a party that promotes Virtue, Law and Order, but they do not see that this government has given up what made our country's reputation and dignity.
The shame, Mr. Toews, is there, in this renunciation, and not elsewhere.
Free thought - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold mining company has filed a six million-dollar defamation suit against three authors and a penniless small publishing house in an effort to initiate a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in cases of defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic in these unequal fights is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition and scare anyone who dares to look into the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, discussions in Canada are normally held through the exchange of ideas and not by battering.
So all the mine had to do was open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and is rejecting petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can at the same time call for a 'public' debate and disregard the opinions of that same public.
In the vice-presidential world, it seems that the word refers only to the well-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that's a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have a say.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public who support the writers and editors of Black Canada do so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a flag-launching prosecution (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a warning to the authors of Black Canada urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in its entirety, the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich corporations of this world in a country like Canada, under threat of repeated prosecution, who will?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to a reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
The excessive prosecution of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street bailout - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months still needs to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides for: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default, and a right of supervision over the salaries paid to the managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican negotiator Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street", she said.
"That's the bottom line: if we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense", said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had been running at a fast pace in the last few hours, fearing the effect of a further failure on investor sentiment.
The deadline we agreed on was the market opening this morning.
The two US presidential candidates, who were late to the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that it had to come to this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has claimed credit for adding certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of executives of state-rescued businesses.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated for.
But these measures are necessary", he said on American television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
