The $700 billion plan is to buy back with taxpayer money the dubious, risky and unsold assets of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CCS) and leading to a freeze in liquidity and the run-off of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who had the first draft of the agreement overturned last week.
We are believed to have come out of this impasse since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of struggling companies should only be insured by the government, rather than bought.
To round out the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recoup its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion, to which 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
