The hearings on the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organisation, on a permanent and regular basis, having caused particularly significant damage.
The prosecution argued that the money from the grants was being spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were being justified by false invoices.
The money from the State and municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement on the one hand and to the pockets of certain individuals on the other.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the grants obtained by issuing invoices for costs, behind which no actual benefit was provided and thus the associations never fulfilled their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large portion of the bills were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the pills at Kiskunhalas.
The names of the companies to be included on the invoices were decided, inter alia, during the tour of the province north of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the witness, he was supposed to be spotting boarding houses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices they were going to introduce, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drawing up the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "scouting circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
