The psychology of over-bidding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overpricing the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have been able to update the neurological and economic basis for this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be isolated in such a competition, such as an eBay auction, and therefore they even pay a price that is too high.
These studies have attempted to draw a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" by experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method, researchers analyzed the active brain regions of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction, where a key element is the one-third surcharge, the set below the brain stem, called the striatum, would move intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulating" mechanism of the nervous system.
Researchers say that the reason for the price increase is that people flee the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists in this research group carried out further analyses of financial surveillance.
In these, three groups overbid against one partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received the 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is actually that the emphasis was on winning in one group, while the emphasis was on failing in the other.
In proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "failure" team were willing to place higher bets than those of the control group and the "win" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Each of these accounts explained the phenomena observed at auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the pride in risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories and now lead to a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that there are 100 000 patients with hepatitis in Hungary, but only 7 000 are receiving treatment, because many patients do not know they have the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name for infections of the liver caused by various viruses.
There is a lot of similarity between their symptoms, and the inflammation of the liver and the jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and the diseases they cause are different.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers are advised to get vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food, usually accompanied by general malaise, weakness, stomach upset, and nausea.
Then a visible yellowing develops on the skin and white of the eye, the stool becomes lighter and the urine becomes darker in color.
Worldwide, a million people die each year from the most serious forms of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten patients, according to estimates, receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they have the virus because the pathogen is subtly destroying liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 to 30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as are regular screening tests.
The contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had received a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are an estimated 200 million people worldwide with chronic hepatitis C.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as you notice symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first observed in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does believing in God make you feel less pain?
According to recent research, religious belief is a kind of painkiller, which has already helped make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph reported that researchers at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to determine how much belief in God might affect the tolerance of human pain.
In this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists were electrocuted while each was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results show that Catholics have been able to rule out much of the suffering.
Using a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the university.
More specifically, the experiment is carried out as follows: an instrument which emits sparks and diffuses the electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the subject.
The researchers asked the participants in the experiment to look at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not unlike the first, was about its calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
Catholics said that upon seeing the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe", "cared for", and "calmed down, and peace came over them".
When they saw the painting with a religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they saw Leonardo's painting.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the experiment, believes that you can achieve the same effect with any other strong image, in atheists, provided you find the right photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually changes our personality", Wright added.
After these excellent results, the only question remains: what effect would it have on the pain regulation of the subjects if we showed the faithful a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would seeing a better quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
You are what you reveal about yourself.
On its tenth anniversary, Google says it can be found deep in people's pockets just like the sky above their heads, knowing where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consulted, and what their interests were.
But that is not enough, says Eric Schmidt, one of the most influential people in society.
And as for the skeptics who draw parallels with Orwell's horror vision, they don't see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times recently that Google's main ambition is to collect even more information about its users, which is necessary if the founders of Google are to be able to meet their original goal which was: "Let's collect all the information in the world in one system".
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of global scrambling, they are still at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What can I do tomorrow?" or "What would be the best job for me?" However, software will not be able to answer such simple questions until it knows enough about users.
It is not entirely clear to all Internet users that the words used during internet searches, the IP address of the computer that initiates the search and the pages subsequently accessed by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search programme launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can see what they have searched for, what they have clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long run, Recommendations, a programme based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and registered preferences.
What if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my work is?" ask users, who are worried about Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can provoke fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly rebellion against power that can provoke a counter-reaction among Internet users.
It is a confirmed fact, however, that the search terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases they are passed on to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of recent time is the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public website called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious netizens were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, in a showdown with the electronic legal protection organization EFF, proved its right to the FBI in court, and the ruling states that in the future, Google will still not be required by any clause of the Constitution to disclose information on the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won in connection with the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, it failed to obtain the lists of searches by private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords for the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is being criticized by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their private sphere and their private domain suffer when they start using Google services, and therefore they attack them in the spirit of revolt against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savages" bringing together the computer enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic users that are emerging in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the "fashion corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, branded as the world's invader because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its applications.
The reason may also be that geeks see very precisely the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what Web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword in recent years, is pulling right behind it.
Indeed, Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the communication channels that are available to us, and while the dimensions of these change one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep blogs, where their latest photo galleries that they have stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
While there are many examples, such as the girlfriend who understands easily from the morning photos taken by the circle of friends with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or the company that fired one of its employees, just for the sincere opinions that the latter wrote on his blog about top management, we can be sure of one thing: the term privacy is totally reconsidered nowadays.
Who lives an online life is made up of what they show themselves, and this is how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's youth.
Anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to try to circumvent Google's monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that they cannot be found is not small. Google's online services, from word processing to image processing to reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge parks of servers and which do not fit our best profile, having existed until today.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
