Smart Car Imitates the Stealing of the Bumblebee
What better way to develop obstacle avoidance technology than by mimicking an obstacle detector that already exists in nature?
Like the bee thing.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, humming bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robot control system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
Each bee flies into its own oval-shaped space, which is actually very similar to our secure protective shell", explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the brand's technology research and development and public relations department.
The beekeeper's eye is of vital importance, since it can see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the multifaceted eye, engineers have developed the idea of the laser telescope.
The radar detects obstacles at a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it into an evasive maneuver.
The detection of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, and then the mini-autobot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid a collision.
Unlike any system currently in place, this avoidance is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not, the mini-robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is currently considered inevitable.
This whole process has to reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot be up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
So instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotational motion, acceleration and deceleration as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries which are lighter and have a larger energy concentration, which makes their lifetime longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
Andoh says it's the instinctive intelligent reaction that's paramount, not the data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism only has to process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, and in this way it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
We don't need memory with a gigabyte capacity, or even megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards designing technology for instantaneous avoidance, which Nissan estimates will be introduced into mass-produced cars within the next decade.
Another application could be to incorporate it into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his way.
