On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill that will be called the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, and then its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The programme also differs from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion should be spent all at once on the repurchase of bonds with doubtful credits.
From now on, no more than half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be released immediately after the law is passed by Congress, probably on Monday. That first amount will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy dubious loans from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The programme will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion is dependent on a new order from Congress.
