Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007, reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1,1% compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier they decreased by 3,9%.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared with the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared with the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent, by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry only slightly increased by 0.1% compared with July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2,8 per cent), with bags and belts manufacturing first with a monthly increase of 4,6 per cent, followed by footwear production with a monthly increase of 2,5 per cent.
The higher price level of plastics and chemicals has resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6%).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4%), the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.9%), and a slight increase in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, printing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry increased by between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the sectors of electricity, gas, steam and water supply, which are a major factor in the national industrial activity, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sector, it was the oil processing sector which saw the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacturing sector of metal products, prices rose by 13.2%, while in the important food, beverage and tobacco sector prices rose by 11%.
Price decreases were recorded in the textile and textile products sectors (2.5%) and in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3%).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase ranged from 0.6 to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole of the processing industry, prices rose by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sectoral allocation, the sectors initiating profit on investment showed the most significant monthly price increase in August (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3%, while those in the energy and further processing sectors were unchanged compared with the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and materials for further processing sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, inflation was recorded at 6.8%, while in the profit-making sectors, it was down by 1.4%.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared with the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over the 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, and compared with August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
