The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, as the representative of the current Presidency of the European Union, has opened in Paris today.
In her speech to the plenary, as one of the main spokespersons for the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP from the European People's Party (EPP), drew attention to segregation in education, as it is the violation of rights that most affects Roma children and is therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of European legal protection and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities, are among those invited to take part in the consultation.
According to the press office of the Fidesz Popular Party group, Járóka warned that apart from the discrimination in hiring, Roma are disappearing from the labour market, primarily because of their low qualifications.
"The overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have a high school diploma, and because of poor quality of primary education, only a small proportion have the opportunity to obtain a university degree".
Járóka also stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the promotion of other fundamental rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children means strengthening the economies of the EU Member States.
The MEP believes that awareness of these relationships should be raised as widely as possible, including among Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the greater the chances for him to become a productive member of the labour market; by the taxes paid from his income and consumption, he contributes to the state budget.
"As citizens of the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and protected from poor quality and sectarian education", said Lívia Járóka.
The Commission is also proposing that the European Parliament should be consulted on the draft directive on the protection of individuals with regard to the processing of personal data and on the protection of personal data.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give Roma children the opportunities offered by democracy so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe", Járóka said.
In the name of the 'European Year for Equal Opportunities for All', the objective of the Equality Summit in Europe, which has been held annually since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination at European and Member State level.
