If you point at an MP3 player, you're putting your hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for a prolonged period using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is the message from the European Commission, which quoted the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (CSRseri) in the EU, published today, in a press release issued in Brussels.
"This scientific report", we read in the footnote, "shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than one hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably", says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific evidence shows that this is a clear risk and we must act quickly.
The most important thing is to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public domain.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and able to keep pace with new technologies.'
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
'The scientists confirm that there is good reason for concern, and that the European Commission will now consider with Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical instruments and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about the hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to reduce this data by means of solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure duration.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical instruments, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the currently applicable limits for the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This is the case for 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
The Commission has been ordered to leave Rome for the future of the capital.
Today we start, in March we finish, in June we draw the sums.
This is the schedule set by the Capitol for the work of the Commission for the Future of Rome, which took place this morning at the new headquarters behind the Thermae de Caracalla.
In six months, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will draw up the guidelines for Rome.
In March, when they are finished, the Committee and the City Council will evaluate the analyses and projects, in order to present the Strategic Plan for Rome in June with the 'official stamp' of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented", Alemanno stresses. "It will have to propose ideas for the development of Rome which will be of use to the political decision-makers, who remain the Committee and the Municipal Council.
No overlapping roles, but only the desire to have a corner where to elaborate a grand plan for Rome.
In March, it will have completed its tasks and then disappear, as this experiment must have a precise time duration.
In June, the mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan resulting from the work carried out by the Commission for the Future of Rome, the Capital".
To those who accuse the Commission of being useless, since its opinions will not be binding, Alemanno replies: "It all depends on the work the Commission will be able to do and the quality of its proposals.
If quality is there, as in France thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome, I am sure its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics is overwhelmed by the management of the day-to-day and emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the contrary, want to look ahead, and further, towards a deeper perspective, working seriously on the development of Rome and its future".
The Mayor of Rome also wanted to emphasise that 'this Commission is not a useless body or a bureaucratic body: it is absolutely free, and will not cost the citizens of Rome a single euro, and will be used to study and involve the best intellectuals who express the Capital.
For Alemanno, "a draft strategic reference, neither firm nor immobile, is needed to enable our city to improve, which it absolutely needs, while thinking about its future in a united spirit".
A future which, the mayor of Rome said, "will not be confined to the usual municipal boundaries, but will look further" not only in terms of the future metropolitan city and its legal status as capital, but also "in terms of the role that Rome can and must have as the capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
