The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon was already manifested a few days ago, with the House of Representatives voting against the $700 billion bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this, reporting that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, even more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, which made itself felt in a despotic way with the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake is foreshadowing or is already allowing to happen: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not just here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to have accelerated the phenomena that have been covered up for some time, to the point that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of state and sovereign, in relation to a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with the outside world, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also a constituency.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalisation seems to be out of the question or, at least, has little to say: the clear evidence is provided by the European Union, which, divided as usual between the various interests and the various national strategies, is unable to decide on any common policy.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit allocation: when you go through a difficult period, it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimacy to use them - two resources of inestimable value, elements which no market or international organization can ever have available in an analogous way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to settle its accounts more and more with things that are not quite material, like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely bound to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So whoever is sovereign certainly has more cards than whoever is not, that is, whoever has the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second innovation which, however, involves a fracture.
Which means Territory, State, Government, inevitably means Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for someone who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leadership, economic species that have proven inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And then there is something even more profound, in a sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of alienation that tends to involve the entire class of managers in an increasing number of Western countries.
This further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites up to now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership is fuelling, in a subterranean way, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the recent changes in collective moods, from the conservative rise in Austria in Bavaria, to the fall of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the US Congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, some would say, are having more and more difficulty, which is not today, to understand and therefore to represent the deepest layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is potentially strengthening, increasing and agitating in an excessive way.
In view of all this, it seems frankly exaggerated to talk of a current "mass revolt" on the agenda.
But, as they say, keeping your eyes wide open is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spider-Man.
That's the goal of several research centers in the United States, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
Using a piece of adhesive just two and a half square centimeters in size, the researchers were able to hold a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
THE US magazine Science published the findings of researchers at the University of Dayton, the University of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the research team, is an evolution of the ones we know that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the gecko's legs, which are covered with microscopic hairs that help the animal to maintain a perfect grip.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the feet of these reptiles, and at the same time, it is easily detached from the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as temporary adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe it's to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe it is, but researchers are thinking about a much less fascinating use, like connecting electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at the moment.
OTHER RESEARCH - The University of California, Berkeley, is also engaged in research on a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, researchers in California have developed a glue made of hairlike microfibers that cleans itself of dust when moving on a surface to ensure perfect and consistent adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in the summer because they are appetizing and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, warns of the dangers of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if they are associated with the ingestion of certain medicines. At the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he raises a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines, negating their beneficial effects and putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stamina and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
RISK MEDICALS - The Italian Medicines Agency itself had reported the news in a newsletter dated two years ago, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this combination and to be careful what they drink, if they take medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
DO NOT PAMPELMUSE - According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit medication.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices is long.
Michele Carruba, head of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are usually immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies, which will have to change the drug information notes if necessary.
It is always advisable to read the leaflets of the medicines you are taking, and if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but clearly address the doctor or pharmacist", the expert told Ansa.
