Open Office, this is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package.
OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source personal productivity suite, aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office package is being shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, and the revised and less austere interface, to other more important features, such as compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system, and support for the new ODF format (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphics module, keeping the original appearance of the page.
On this front, it is also possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents which combine the typical graphics of Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a word processor.
The collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on the modifications, in the elaboration of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working on bringing some of the functionality of OpenOffice to the web, and in the coming weeks they should release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and is in addition to the English version that has been on Mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is available as usual for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to the home or workplace.
And if the theme of free can be a means of spreading it in the home, it is precisely in business, where the Open Office suite faces the great challenge, already being able to count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
The Commission has also been involved in the development of a number of initiatives to improve the quality of the services provided by the SMEs.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the video writing equivalent of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint's rival presentations; Dbase, like the famous Access, is the program that allows working on databases; finally Drwa is the graphics module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today we have almost 3.600 million miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version we can even exceed the planned figure.
