Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, cities are celebrating the historic theatres.
Historic movie theaters are closing in favor of multiplexes.
"A city without a cinema is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The picture, by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial towns,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the emergence of large multi-screen theatres in the periphery and the death of the mono-screen theatres in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and undeniable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it's like a friend disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of the way and so many emotions" observes the director of Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, a film that gave Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, tell the whole story: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the major cities have paid the most for the closure: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
