When energy comes from waves, now the big ones come.
This is a huge deposit that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable resources that giants like Chevron have set their eyes on, and now they're trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movement of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in the 1980s, the idea of exploiting marine energy was shelved, but now environmental concerns and the new oil boom are giving the sector a major boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be met by tidal systems.
This would be twice as much as is produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there's the tides and the currents.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it was a revolutionary move.
Two years later, more and more candidates from among those companies which have always been committed to traditional energy are turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean-power technologies", a spokesman for a company associated with the American oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperation with us".
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to enable a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially when you consider that in Alaska, the United States continues to drill for oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are pursuing the sea-based energy route, and the amounts invested to date, although details are not known, indicate, according to observers, growing interest.
Technology to be improved.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, but the fact that marine energy is not doing away with concerns about its environmental impact.
At present, systems like those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in scale, and do not seem to be causing a major problem to the ecosystem.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a higher environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are varied: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys that are connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure from the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine, which in turn, powers a generator.
Power is sent to shore through undersea cables.
Right now, we have four such systems in the design phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could go to a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines from New York's East River.
The movement of water during tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary motion that powers a generator.
Verdant announced that he had a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to draw power.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, is the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and thus more reliable as a source of energy.
And it's precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, are looking to the coast, investing $7.5 million in 2008 and planning to invest up to $35 million in 2009.
